# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: protein-folding-bio
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:protein-folding-bio/anfinsen-s-dogma] Some proteins need the assistance of chaperone proteins to fold properly.
[src:protein-folding-bio/anfinsen-s-dogma] It has been suggested that this disproves Anfinsen's dogma.
[src:protein-folding-bio/anfinsen-s-dogma] However, the chaperones do not appear to affect the final state of the protein; they seem to work primarily by preventing aggregation of several protein molecules prior to the final folded state of the protein.
[src:protein-folding-bio/anfinsen-s-dogma] However, at least some chaperones are required for the proper folding of their subject proteins.
[src:protein-folding-bio/anfinsen-s-dogma] Many proteins can also undergo aggregation and misfolding.
[src:protein-folding-bio/anfinsen-s-dogma] For example, prions are stable conformations of proteins which differ from the native folding state.
[src:protein-folding-bio/anfinsen-s-dogma] In bovine spongiform encephalopathy, native proteins re-fold into a different stable conformation, which causes fatal amyloid buildup.
[src:protein-folding-bio/anfinsen-s-dogma] Other amyloid diseases, including Alzheimer's disease and Parkinson's disease, are also exceptions to Anfinsen's dogma.
[src:protein-folding-bio/anfinsen-s-dogma] Some proteins have multiple native structures, and change their fold based on some external factors.
[src:protein-folding-bio/anfinsen-s-dogma] For example, the KaiB protein complex switches fold throughout the day, acting as a clock for cyanobacteria.
[src:protein-folding-bio/anfinsen-s-dogma] It has been estimated that around 0.5–4% of Protein Data Bank (PDB) proteins switch folds.
[src:protein-folding-bio/anfinsen-s-dogma] The switching between alternative structures is driven by interactions of the protein with small ligands or other proteins, by chemical modifications (such as phosphorylation) or by changed environmental conditions, such as temperature, pH or membrane potential.
[src:protein-folding-bio/anfinsen-s-dogma] Each alternative structure may either correspond to the global minimum of free energy of the protein at the given conditions or be kinetically trapped in a higher local minimum of free energy.
[src:protein-folding-bio/chaperone-protein] In molecular biology, **molecular chaperones** are proteins that assist the conformational folding or unfolding of proteins or macromolecular protein complexes.
[src:protein-folding-bio/chaperone-protein] There are a number of classes of molecular chaperones, all of which function to assist large proteins in proper protein folding during or after synthesis, and after partial denaturation.
[src:protein-folding-bio/chaperone-protein] Chaperones are also involved in the translocation of proteins for proteolysis.
[src:protein-folding-bio/chaperone-protein] The first molecular chaperones discovered were a type of assembly chaperones which assist in the assembly of nucleosomes from folded histones and DNA.
[src:protein-folding-bio/chaperone-protein] One major function of molecular chaperones is to prevent the aggregation of misfolded proteins, thus many chaperone proteins are classified as heat shock proteins, as the tendency for protein aggregation is increased by heat stress.
[src:protein-folding-bio/chaperone-protein] The majority of molecular chaperones do not convey any steric information for protein folding, and instead assist in protein folding by binding to and stabilizing folding intermediates until the polypeptide chain is fully translated.
[src:protein-folding-bio/chaperone-protein] The specific mode of function of chaperones differs based on their target proteins and location.
[src:protein-folding-bio/chaperone-protein] Various approaches have been applied to study the structure, dynamics and functioning of chaperones.
[src:protein-folding-bio/chaperone-protein] Bulk biochemical measurements have informed us on the protein folding efficiency, and prevention of aggregation when chaperones are present during protein folding.
[src:protein-folding-bio/chaperone-protein] Recent advances in single-molecule analysis have brought insights into structural heterogeneity of chaperones, folding intermediates and affinity of chaperones for unstructured and structured protein chains.
[src:protein-folding-bio/chaperone-protein] Many chaperones are heat shock proteins, that is, proteins expressed in response to elevated temperatures or other cellular stresses.
[src:protein-folding-bio/chaperone-protein] Heat shock protein chaperones are classified based on their observed molecular weights into Hsp60, Hsp70, Hsp90, Hsp104, and small Hsps.
[src:protein-folding-bio/chaperone-protein] The Hsp60 family of protein chaperones are termed chaperonins, and are characterized by a stacked double-ring structure and are found in prokaryotes, in the cytosol of eukaryotes, and in mitochondria.
[src:protein-folding-bio/chaperone-protein] Some chaperone systems work as foldases: they support the folding of proteins in an ATP-dependent manner (for example, the GroEL/GroES or the DnaK/DnaJ/GrpE system).
[src:protein-folding-bio/chaperone-protein] Although most newly synthesized proteins can fold in absence of chaperones, a minority strictly requires them for the same.
[src:protein-folding-bio/chaperone-protein] Other chaperones work as holdases: they bind folding intermediates to prevent their aggregation, for example DnaJ or Hsp33.
[src:protein-folding-bio/chaperone-protein] Chaperones can also work as disaggregases, which interact with aberrant protein assemblies and revert them to monomers.
[src:protein-folding-bio/chaperone-protein] Some chaperones can assist in protein degradation, leading proteins to protease systems, such as the ubiquitin-proteasome system in eukaryotes.
[src:protein-folding-bio/chaperone-protein] Chaperone proteins participate in the folding of over half of all mammalian proteins.
[src:protein-folding-bio/chaperone-protein] Macromolecular crowding may be important in chaperone function.
[src:protein-folding-bio/chaperone-protein] The crowded environment of the cytosol can accelerate the folding process, since a compact folded protein will occupy less volume than an unfolded protein chain.
[src:protein-folding-bio/chaperone-protein] However, crowding can reduce the yield of correctly folded protein by increasing protein aggregation.
[src:protein-folding-bio/chaperone-protein] Crowding may also increase the effectiveness of the chaperone proteins such as GroEL, which could counteract this reduction in folding efficiency.
[src:protein-folding-bio/chaperone-protein] Some highly specific 'steric chaperones' convey unique structural information onto proteins, which cannot be folded spontaneously.
[src:protein-folding-bio/chaperone-protein] Such proteins violate Anfinsen's dogma, requiring protein dynamics to fold correctly.
[src:protein-folding-bio/chaperone-protein] Other types of chaperones are involved in transport across membranes, for example membranes of the mitochondria and endoplasmic reticulum (ER) in eukaryotes.
[src:protein-folding-bio/chaperone-protein] A bacterial translocation-specific chaperone SecB maintains newly synthesized precursor polypeptide chains in a translocation-competent (generally unfolded) state and guides them to the translocon.
[src:protein-folding-bio/chaperone-protein] New functions for chaperones continue to be discovered, such as bacterial adhesin activity, induction of aggregation towards non-amyloid aggregates, suppression of toxic protein oligomers via their clustering, and in responding to diseases linked to protein aggregation and cancer maintenance.
[src:protein-folding-bio/chaperone-protein] In human cell lines, chaperone proteins were found to make up ~10% of the gross proteome mass, and are ubiquitously and highly expressed across human tissues.
[src:protein-folding-bio/chaperone-protein] Chaperones are found extensively in the endoplasmic reticulum (ER), since protein synthesis often occurs in this area.
[src:protein-folding-bio/chaperone-protein] In the endoplasmic reticulum (ER) there are general, lectin- and non-classical molecular chaperones that moderate protein folding.
[src:protein-folding-bio/chaperone-protein] There are many different families of chaperones; each family acts to aid protein folding in a different way.
[src:protein-folding-bio/chaperone-protein] In bacteria like *E. coli*, many of these proteins are highly expressed under conditions of high stress, for example, when the bacterium is placed in high temperatures, thus heat shock protein chaperones are the most extensive.
[src:protein-folding-bio/chaperone-protein] A variety of nomenclatures are in use for chaperones.
[src:protein-folding-bio/chaperone-protein] As heat shock proteins, the names are classically formed by "Hsp" followed by the approximate molecular mass in kilodaltons; such names are commonly used for eukaryotes such as yeast.
[src:protein-folding-bio/chaperone-protein] The bacterial names have more varied forms, and refer directly to their apparent function at discovery.
[src:protein-folding-bio/chaperone-protein] For example, "GroEL" originally stands for "phage growth defect, overcome by mutation in phage gene E, large subunit".
[src:protein-folding-bio/chaperone-protein] It has been noted that increased expression of Hsp70 proteins in the cell results in a decreased tendency toward apoptosis.
[src:protein-folding-bio/chaperone-protein] Although a precise mechanistic understanding has yet to be determined, it is known that Hsp70s have a high-affinity bound state to unfolded proteins when bound to ADP, and a low-affinity state when bound to ATP.
[src:protein-folding-bio/chaperone-protein] It is thought that many Hsp70s crowd around an unfolded substrate, stabilizing it and preventing aggregation until the unfolded molecule folds properly, at which time the Hsp70s lose affinity for the molecule and diffuse away.
[src:protein-folding-bio/chaperone-protein] Hsp70 also acts as a mitochondrial and chloroplastic molecular chaperone in eukaryotes.
[src:protein-folding-bio/chaperone-protein] Each Hsp90 has an ATP-binding domain, a middle domain, and a dimerization domain.
[src:protein-folding-bio/chaperone-protein] Originally thought to clamp onto their substrate protein (also known as a client protein) upon binding ATP, the recently published structures by Vaughan *et al.* and Ali *et al.* indicate that client proteins may bind externally to both the N-terminal and middle domains of Hsp90.
[src:protein-folding-bio/chaperone-protein] Hsp90 may also require co-chaperones-like immunophilins, Sti1, p50 (Cdc37), and Aha1, and also cooperates with the Hsp70 chaperone system.
[src:protein-folding-bio/chaperone-protein] Proteins in the Hsp100/Clp family form large hexameric structures with unfoldase activity in the presence of ATP.
[src:protein-folding-bio/chaperone-protein] These proteins are thought to function as chaperones by processively threading client proteins through a small 20 Å (2 nm) pore, thereby giving each client protein a second chance to fold.
[src:protein-folding-bio/chaperone-protein] Some of these Hsp100 chaperones, like ClpA and ClpX, associate with the double-ringed tetradecameric serine protease ClpP; instead of catalyzing the refolding of client proteins, these complexes are responsible for the targeted destruction of tagged and misfolded proteins.
[src:protein-folding-bio/chaperone-protein] Hsp104, the Hsp100 of Saccharomyces cerevisiae, is essential for the propagation of many yeast prions.
[src:protein-folding-bio/chaperone-protein] Deletion of the HSP104 gene results in cells that are unable to propagate certain prions.
[src:protein-folding-bio/chaperone-protein] The genes of bacteriophage (phage) T4 that encode proteins with a role in determining phage T4 structure were identified using conditional lethal mutants.
[src:protein-folding-bio/chaperone-protein] Most of these proteins proved to be either major or minor structural components of the completed phage particle.
[src:protein-folding-bio/chaperone-protein] However among the gene products (gps) necessary for phage assembly, Snustad identified a group of gps that act catalytically rather than being incorporated themselves into the phage structure.
[src:protein-folding-bio/chaperone-protein] These gps were gp26, gp31, gp38, gp51, gp28, and gp4 [gene 4 is synonymous with genes 50 and 65, and thus the gp can be designated gp4(50)(65)].
[src:protein-folding-bio/chaperone-protein] The first four of these six gene products have since been recognized as being chaperone proteins.
[src:protein-folding-bio/chaperone-protein] Additionally, gp40, gp57A, gp63 and gpwac have also now been identified as chaperones.
[src:protein-folding-bio/chaperone-protein] Phage T4 morphogenesis is divided into three independent pathways: the head, the tail and the long tail fiber pathways as detailed by Yap and Rossman.
[src:protein-folding-bio/chaperone-protein] With regard to head morphogenesis, chaperone gp31 interacts with the bacterial host chaperone GroEL to promote proper folding of the major head capsid protein gp23.
[src:protein-folding-bio/chaperone-protein] Chaperone gp40 participates in the assembly of gp20, thus aiding in the formation of the connector complex that initiates head procapsid assembly.
[src:protein-folding-bio/chaperone-protein] Gp4(50)(65), although not specifically listed as a chaperone, acts catalytically as a nuclease that appears to be essential for morphogenesis by cleaving packaged DNA to enable the joining of heads to tails.
[src:protein-folding-bio/chaperone-protein] During overall tail assembly, chaperone proteins gp26 and gp51 are necessary for baseplate hub assembly.
[src:protein-folding-bio/chaperone-protein] Gp57A is required for correct folding of gp12, a structural component of the baseplate short tail fibers.
[src:protein-folding-bio/chaperone-protein] Synthesis of the long tail fibers depends on the chaperone protein gp57A that is needed for the trimerization of gp34 and gp37, the major structural proteins of the tail fibers.
[src:protein-folding-bio/chaperone-protein] The chaperone protein gp38 is also required for the proper folding of gp37.
[src:protein-folding-bio/chaperone-protein] Chaperone proteins gp63 and gpwac are employed in attachment of the long tail fibers to the tail baseplate.
[src:protein-folding-bio/chaperone-protein] The investigation of chaperones has a long history.
[src:protein-folding-bio/chaperone-protein] The term "molecular chaperone" appeared first in the literature in 1978, and was invented by Ron Laskey to describe the ability of a nuclear protein called nucleoplasmin to prevent the aggregation of folded histone proteins with DNA during the assembly of nucleosomes.
[src:protein-folding-bio/chaperone-protein] John Ellis in 1987 to describe proteins that mediated the post-translational assembly of protein complexes.
[src:protein-folding-bio/chaperone-protein] In 1988, it was realised that similar proteins mediated this process in both prokaryotes and eukaryotes.
[src:protein-folding-bio/chaperone-protein] The details of this process were determined in 1989, when the ATP-dependent protein folding was demonstrated *in vitro*.
[src:protein-folding-bio/chaperone-protein] There are many disorders associated with mutations in genes encoding chaperones (i.e. multisystem proteinopathy) that can affect muscle, bone and/or the central nervous system.
[src:protein-folding-bio/hydrophobic-effect] The **hydrophobic effect** is the observed tendency of nonpolar substances to aggregate in an aqueous solution and to be excluded by water.
[src:protein-folding-bio/hydrophobic-effect] The word hydrophobic literally means "water-fearing", and it describes the segregation of water and nonpolar substances, which maximizes the entropy of water and minimizes the area of contact between water and nonpolar molecules.
[src:protein-folding-bio/hydrophobic-effect] In terms of thermodynamics, the hydrophobic effect is the free energy change of water surrounding a solute.
[src:protein-folding-bio/hydrophobic-effect] A positive free energy change of the surrounding solvent indicates hydrophobicity, whereas a negative free energy change implies hydrophilicity.
[src:protein-folding-bio/hydrophobic-effect] The hydrophobic effect is responsible for the separation of a mixture of oil and water into its two components.
[src:protein-folding-bio/hydrophobic-effect] It is also responsible for effects related to biology, including: cell membrane and vesicle formation, protein folding, insertion of membrane proteins into the nonpolar lipid environment and protein-small molecule associations.
[src:protein-folding-bio/hydrophobic-effect] Hence the hydrophobic effect is essential to life.
[src:protein-folding-bio/hydrophobic-effect] Substances for which this effect is observed are known as hydrophobes.
[src:protein-folding-bio/hydrophobic-effect] Amphiphiles are molecules that have both hydrophobic and hydrophilic domains.
[src:protein-folding-bio/hydrophobic-effect] Detergents are composed of amphiphiles that allow hydrophobic molecules to be solubilized in water by forming micelles and bilayers (as in soap bubbles).
[src:protein-folding-bio/hydrophobic-effect] They are also important to cell membranes composed of amphiphilic phospholipids that prevent the internal aqueous environment of a cell from mixing with external water.
[src:protein-folding-bio/hydrophobic-effect] In the case of protein folding, the hydrophobic effect is important to understanding the structure of proteins that have hydrophobic amino acids (such as valine, leucine, isoleucine, phenylalanine, tryptophan and methionine) clustered together within the protein.
[src:protein-folding-bio/hydrophobic-effect] Structures of globular proteins have a hydrophobic core in which hydrophobic side chains are buried from water, which stabilizes the folded state.
[src:protein-folding-bio/hydrophobic-effect] Charged and polar side chains are situated on the solvent-exposed surface where they interact with surrounding water molecules.
[src:protein-folding-bio/hydrophobic-effect] Minimizing the number of hydrophobic side chains exposed to water is the principal driving force behind the folding process, although formation of hydrogen bonds within the protein also stabilizes protein structure.
[src:protein-folding-bio/hydrophobic-effect] The energetics of DNA tertiary-structure assembly were determined to be driven by the hydrophobic effect, in addition to Watson–Crick base pairing, which is responsible for sequence selectivity, and stacking interactions between the aromatic bases.
[src:protein-folding-bio/hydrophobic-effect] In biochemistry, the hydrophobic effect can be used to separate mixtures of proteins based on their hydrophobicity.
[src:protein-folding-bio/hydrophobic-effect] Column chromatography with a hydrophobic stationary phase such as phenyl-sepharose will cause more hydrophobic proteins to travel more slowly, while less hydrophobic ones elute from the column sooner.
[src:protein-folding-bio/hydrophobic-effect] To achieve better separation, a salt may be added (higher concentrations of salt increase the hydrophobic effect) and its concentration decreased as the separation progresses.
[src:protein-folding-bio/hydrophobic-effect] The origin of the hydrophobic effect is not fully understood.
[src:protein-folding-bio/hydrophobic-effect] Some argue that the hydrophobic interaction is mostly an entropic effect originating from the disruption of highly dynamic hydrogen bonds between molecules of liquid water by the nonpolar solute.
[src:protein-folding-bio/hydrophobic-effect] A hydrocarbon chain or a similar nonpolar region of a large molecule is incapable of forming hydrogen bonds with water.
[src:protein-folding-bio/hydrophobic-effect] Introduction of such a non-hydrogen bonding surface into water causes disruption of the hydrogen bonding network between water molecules.
[src:protein-folding-bio/hydrophobic-effect] The hydrogen bonds are reoriented tangentially to such surface to minimize disruption of the hydrogen bonded 3D network of water molecules, and this leads to a structured water "cage" around the nonpolar surface.
[src:protein-folding-bio/hydrophobic-effect] The water molecules that form the "cage" (or clathrate) have restricted mobility.
[src:protein-folding-bio/hydrophobic-effect] In the solvation shell of small nonpolar particles, the restriction amounts to some 10%.
[src:protein-folding-bio/hydrophobic-effect] For example, in the case of dissolved xenon at room temperature a mobility restriction of 30% has been found.
[src:protein-folding-bio/hydrophobic-effect] In the case of larger nonpolar molecules, the reorientational and translational motion of the water molecules in the solvation shell may be restricted by a factor of two to four; thus, at 25 °C the reorientational correlation time of water increases from 2 to 4-8 picoseconds.
[src:protein-folding-bio/hydrophobic-effect] Generally, this leads to significant losses in translational and rotational entropy of water molecules and makes the process unfavorable in terms of the free energy in the system.
[src:protein-folding-bio/hydrophobic-effect] By aggregating together, nonpolar molecules reduce the surface area exposed to water and minimize their disruptive effect.
[src:protein-folding-bio/hydrophobic-effect] The hydrophobic effect can be quantified by measuring the partition coefficients of non-polar molecules between water and non-polar solvents.
[src:protein-folding-bio/hydrophobic-effect] The partition coefficients can be transformed to free energy of transfer which includes enthalpic and entropic components, *ΔG = ΔH - TΔS*.
[src:protein-folding-bio/hydrophobic-effect] These components are experimentally determined by calorimetry.
[src:protein-folding-bio/hydrophobic-effect] At the higher temperature, when water molecules become more mobile, this energy gain decreases along with the entropic component.
[src:protein-folding-bio/hydrophobic-effect] The hydrophobic effect depends on the temperature, which leads to "cold denaturation" of proteins.
[src:protein-folding-bio/hydrophobic-effect] The hydrophobic effect can be calculated by comparing the free energy of solvation with bulk water.
[src:protein-folding-bio/hydrophobic-effect] In this way, the hydrophobic effect not only can be localized but also decomposed into enthalpic and entropic contributions.
[src:protein-folding-bio/levinthal-s-paradox] In 1969, Cyrus Levinthal noted that, because of the many degrees of freedom in an unfolded polypeptide chain, the molecule has an astronomical number of possible conformations.
[src:protein-folding-bio/levinthal-s-paradox] An estimate of 10300 was made in one of his papers (often incorrectly cited as the 1968 paper).
[src:protein-folding-bio/levinthal-s-paradox] For example, a polypeptide of 100 residues will have 200 different phi and psi bond angles, two for each residue.
[src:protein-folding-bio/levinthal-s-paradox] If each torsion angle can be in one of three stable conformations, the protein may adopt a maximum of 3200 different conformations, without even considering interactions between residues or the conformations of side-chains.
[src:protein-folding-bio/levinthal-s-paradox] Therefore, if a protein were to reach its correctly folded configuration by sequentially sampling all possible conformations, it would need more time than the age of the universe to find its native conformation.
[src:protein-folding-bio/levinthal-s-paradox] This remains true even if conformations are sampled at rapid nanosecond or picosecond rates.
[src:protein-folding-bio/levinthal-s-paradox] The "paradox" is that most small proteins fold spontaneously on a millisecond or even microsecond time scale.
[src:protein-folding-bio/levinthal-s-paradox] Insights into this paradox have been advanced by computational approaches to protein structure prediction.
[src:protein-folding-bio/levinthal-s-paradox] Levinthal himself was aware that proteins fold spontaneously and on short timescales.
[src:protein-folding-bio/levinthal-s-paradox] Indeed, the protein folding intermediates and the partially folded transition states were experimentally detected, which explains the fast protein folding.
[src:protein-folding-bio/levinthal-s-paradox] Protein folding can be understood as a multidimensional optimization problem within a funnel-like energy landscape.
[src:protein-folding-bio/levinthal-s-paradox] Any particular configuration of amino acids has a corresponding stability, and the protein will spontaneously follow its energetic gradient toward higher stability states.
[src:protein-folding-bio/levinthal-s-paradox] This tendency directs the process of folding and dramatically shrinks the space of feasible structures the protein might adopt.
[src:protein-folding-bio/levinthal-s-paradox] The protein traverses this landscape of energetic states to its native state, found at the bottom of the funnel.
[src:protein-folding-bio/levinthal-s-paradox] This was shown by Christian Anfinsen in his famous experiments with ribonuclease A, demonstrating that an unfolded protein can refold to its native, functional structure, even in the absence of cellular machinery.
[src:protein-folding-bio/levinthal-s-paradox] This validated Anfinsen's thermodynamic hypothesis, also known as Anfinsen's dogma, which states that the native structure of a protein is the state in which it has a minimum of free energy.
[src:protein-folding-bio/levinthal-s-paradox] In the process of folding it is possible for proteins to become trapped in intermediate states, a locally optimal state, but not a globally optimal state.
[src:protein-folding-bio/levinthal-s-paradox] This problem is addressed in part by chaperones, proteins which assist in the folding process, which help in bringing unfolded intermediates to their native state.
[src:protein-folding-bio/levinthal-s-paradox] However, protein folding does not simply begin with a fully synthesized, unfolded peptide chain.
[src:protein-folding-bio/levinthal-s-paradox] In cellular systems, folding commonly begins while the protein is being produced in the ribosome.
[src:protein-folding-bio/levinthal-s-paradox] As each amino acid is added to the chain, residues can adopt secondary and tertiary structures, a process known as cotranslational folding.
[src:protein-folding-bio/levinthal-s-paradox] According to Edward Trifonov and Igor Berezovsky, proteins fold by subunits (modules) of the size of 25–30 amino acids.
[src:protein-folding-bio/levinthal-s-paradox] The problem of protein folding is increasingly being answered by computational methods.
[src:protein-folding-bio/levinthal-s-paradox] Some computational approaches to protein structure prediction have sought to identify and simulate the mechanism of protein folding.
[src:protein-folding-bio/levinthal-s-paradox] The development of tools such as AlphaFold leverage machine learning and the known structures of homologous proteins to predict unknown structures with high accuracy.
[src:protein-folding-bio/levinthal-s-paradox] Levinthal's paradox was cited on the first page of the Scientific Background to the 2024 Nobel Prize in Chemistry (awarded to David Baker, Demis Hassabis, and John M.
[src:protein-folding-bio/levinthal-s-paradox] Jumper for computational protein design and protein structure prediction) by way of demonstrating the sheer scale of the problem given the astronomical number of permutations.
[src:protein-folding-bio/molten-globule] Protein folding is navigated by a dynamic interplay of secondary and tertiary interactions.
[src:protein-folding-bio/molten-globule] Two extreme folding pathway models have been formulated.
[src:protein-folding-bio/molten-globule] In the first - the framework model - rapidly formed secondary structure elements assemble into a native tertiary structure.
[src:protein-folding-bio/molten-globule] In the second - the hydrophobic collapse model - the formation of a loosely packed tertiary structure precedes secondary structure acquisition.
[src:protein-folding-bio/molten-globule] A nucleation-condensation mechanism involving concomitant formation of short and long-range interactions combines features of both extreme models and thereby represents a unifying mechanism of protein folding.
[src:protein-folding-bio/molten-globule] During folding, proteins span a continuum of conformers starting from the denature and ending at the native state.
[src:protein-folding-bio/molten-globule] Although often considered a statistical random coil, the denatured state can retain residual structure that mediates (re)folding.
[src:protein-folding-bio/molten-globule] For instance, staphylococcal nuclease retains native-like topology in 8M urea, while nonnative lysozyme contains hydrophobic clusters held together by long-range interactions.
[src:protein-folding-bio/molten-globule] By rapidly adjusting experimental conditions to favor native structure formation, relatively compact protein folding intermediates have been observed.
[src:protein-folding-bio/molten-globule] These kinetic intermediates - coined molten globules - exhibit native-like secondary structure and fluctuating tertiary structure.
[src:protein-folding-bio/molten-globule] The molten globule state can also be thermodynamically accessed under mildly denaturing conditions.
[src:protein-folding-bio/molten-globule] It was found, for example, in cytochrome c, which conserves a native-like secondary structure content but without the tightly packed protein interior, under low pH and high salt concentration.
[src:protein-folding-bio/molten-globule] For cytochrome c and some other proteins, it has been shown that the molten globule state is a "thermodynamic state" clearly different both from the native and the denatured state, demonstrating for the first time the existence of a third equilibrium (i.e., intermediate) state.
[src:protein-folding-bio/molten-globule] The term "molten globule" may be used to describe various types of partially-folded protein states found in slightly denaturing conditions such as low pH (generally pH = 2), mild denaturant, or high temperature.
[src:protein-folding-bio/molten-globule] Molten globules are collapsed and generally have some native-like secondary structure but a dynamic tertiary structure as seen by far-UV and near-UV circular dichroism (CD) spectroscopy, respectively.
[src:protein-folding-bio/molten-globule] The molten globule ensembles sampled during protein folding and unfolding are thought to be roughly similar.
[src:protein-folding-bio/molten-globule] The MG structure is believed to lack the close packing of amino acid side chains that characterize the native state ( ${\ce {N}}$ ) of a protein.
[src:protein-folding-bio/molten-globule] Or it may be a continuous transition, with no cooperativity and no apparent "switch" from one form to the other.
[src:protein-folding-bio/molten-globule] One of the difficulties in *de novo* protein design is achieving the side chain packing needed to create a stable native state rather than an ensemble of molten globules.
[src:protein-folding-bio/molten-globule] Given a desired backbone conformation, side chain packing can be designed using variations of the dead-end elimination algorithm; however, attempts to design proteins of novel folds have difficulty using this method due to an absence of plausible backbone models.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] The folding of many proteins begins even during the translation of the polypeptide chain.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] The amino acids interact with each other to produce a well-defined three-dimensional structure, known as the protein's native state.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] This structure is determined by the amino-acid sequence or primary structure.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] The correct three-dimensional structure is essential to function, although some parts of functional proteins may remain unfolded, indicating that protein dynamics are important.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] Failure to fold into a native structure generally produces inactive proteins, but in some instances, misfolded proteins have modified or toxic functionality.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] Several neurodegenerative and other diseases are believed to result from the accumulation of amyloid fibrils formed by misfolded proteins, the infectious varieties of which are known as prions.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] Many allergies are caused by the incorrect folding of some proteins because the immune system does not produce the antibodies for certain protein structures.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] Denaturation of proteins is a process of transition from a folded to an unfolded state.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] It happens in cooking, burns, proteinopathies, and other contexts.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] Residual structure present, if any, in the supposedly unfolded state may form a folding initiation site and guide the subsequent folding reactions.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] The duration of the folding process varies dramatically depending on the protein of interest.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] When studied outside the cell, the slowest folding proteins require many minutes or hours to fold, primarily due to proline isomerization, and must pass through a number of intermediate states, like checkpoints, before the process is complete.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] On the other hand, very small single-domain proteins with lengths of up to a hundred amino acids typically fold in a single step.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] Time scales of milliseconds are the norm, and the fastest known protein folding reactions are complete within a few microseconds.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] The folding time scale of a protein depends on its size, contact order, and circuit topology.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] Understanding and simulating the protein folding process has been an important challenge for computational biology since the late 1960s.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] The primary structure of a protein, its linear amino-acid sequence, determines its native conformation.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] The specific amino acid residues and their position in the polypeptide chain are the determining factors for which portions of the protein fold closely together and form its three-dimensional conformation.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] The amino acid composition is not as important as the sequence.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] The essential fact of folding, however, remains that the amino acid sequence of each protein contains the information that specifies both the native structure and the pathway to attain that state.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] This is not to say that nearly identical amino acid sequences always fold similarly.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] Conformations differ based on environmental factors as well; similar proteins fold differently based on where they are found.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] Formation of a secondary structure is the first step in the folding process that a protein takes to assume its native structure.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] Characteristic of secondary structure are the structures known as alpha helices and beta sheets that fold rapidly because they are stabilized by intramolecular hydrogen bonds, as was first characterized by Linus Pauling.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] Formation of intramolecular hydrogen bonds provides another important contribution to protein stability. α-helices are formed by hydrogen bonding of the backbone to form a spiral shape (refer to figure on the right).
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] The β pleated sheet is a structure that forms with the backbone bending over itself to form the hydrogen bonds (as displayed in the figure to the left).
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] The hydrogen bonds are between the amide hydrogen and carbonyl oxygen of the peptide bond.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] There exists anti-parallel β pleated sheets and parallel β pleated sheets where the stability of the hydrogen bonds is stronger in the anti-parallel β sheet as it hydrogen bonds with the ideal 180 degree angle compared to the slanted hydrogen bonds formed by parallel sheets.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] The α-Helices and β-Sheets are commonly amphipathic, meaning they have a hydrophilic and a hydrophobic portion.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] This ability helps in forming tertiary structure of a protein in which folding occurs so that the hydrophilic sides are facing the aqueous environment surrounding the protein and the hydrophobic sides are facing the hydrophobic core of the protein.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] Secondary structure hierarchically gives way to tertiary structure formation.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] Once the protein's tertiary structure is formed and stabilized by the hydrophobic interactions, there may also be covalent bonding in the form of disulfide bridges formed between two cysteine residues.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] These non-covalent and covalent contacts take a specific topological arrangement in a native structure of a protein.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] Tertiary structure of a protein involves a single polypeptide chain; however, additional interactions of folded polypeptide chains give rise to quaternary structure formation.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] Tertiary structure may give way to the formation of quaternary structure in some proteins, which usually involves the "assembly" or "coassembly" of subunits that have already folded; in other words, multiple polypeptide chains could interact to form a fully functional quaternary protein.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] Folding is a spontaneous process that is mainly guided by hydrophobic interactions, formation of intramolecular hydrogen bonds, van der Waals forces, and it is opposed by conformational entropy.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] The folding time scale of an isolated protein depends on its size, contact order, and circuit topology.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] Inside cells, the process of folding often begins co-translationally, so that the N-terminus of the protein begins to fold while the C-terminal portion of the protein is still being synthesized by the ribosome; however, a protein molecule may fold spontaneously during or after biosynthesis.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] While these macromolecules may be regarded as "folding themselves", the process also depends on the solvent (water or lipid bilayer), the concentration of salts, the pH, the temperature, the possible presence of cofactors and of molecular chaperones.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] Proteins will have limitations on their folding abilities by the restricted bending angles or conformations that are possible.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] These allowable angles of protein folding are described with a two-dimensional plot known as the Ramachandran plot, depicted with psi and phi angles of allowable rotation.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] Protein folding must be thermodynamically favorable within a cell in order for it to be a spontaneous reaction.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] Since it is known that protein folding is a spontaneous reaction, then it must assume a negative Gibbs free energy value.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] Gibbs free energy in protein folding is directly related to enthalpy and entropy.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] For a negative delta G to arise and for protein folding to become thermodynamically favorable, then either enthalpy, entropy, or both terms must be favorable.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] Minimizing the number of hydrophobic side-chains exposed to water is an important driving force behind the folding process.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] The hydrophobic effect is the phenomenon in which the hydrophobic chains of a protein collapse into the core of the protein (away from the hydrophilic environment).
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] In an aqueous environment, the water molecules tend to aggregate around the hydrophobic regions or side chains of the protein, creating water shells of ordered water molecules.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] An ordering of water molecules around a hydrophobic region increases order in a system and therefore contributes a negative change in entropy (less entropy in the system).
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] The water molecules are fixed in these water cages which drives the hydrophobic collapse, or the inward folding of the hydrophobic groups.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] The hydrophobic collapse introduces entropy back to the system via the breaking of the water cages which frees the ordered water molecules.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] The multitude of hydrophobic groups interacting within the core of the globular folded protein contributes a significant amount to protein stability after folding, because of the vastly accumulated van der Waals forces (specifically London Dispersion forces).
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] The hydrophobic effect exists as a driving force in thermodynamics only if there is the presence of an aqueous medium with an amphiphilic molecule containing a large hydrophobic region.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] The strength of hydrogen bonds depends on their environment; thus, H-bonds enveloped in a hydrophobic core contribute more than H-bonds exposed to the aqueous environment to the stability of the native state.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] In proteins with globular folds, hydrophobic amino acids tend to be interspersed along the primary sequence, rather than randomly distributed or clustered together.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] However, proteins that have recently been born de novo, which tend to be intrinsically disordered, show the opposite pattern of hydrophobic amino acid clustering along the primary sequence.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] Molecular chaperones are a class of proteins that aid in the correct folding of other proteins *in vivo*.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] Chaperones exist in all cellular compartments and interact with the polypeptide chain in order to allow the native three-dimensional conformation of the protein to form; however, chaperones themselves are not included in the final structure of the protein they are assisting in.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] Chaperones may assist in folding even when the nascent polypeptide is being synthesized by the ribosome.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] Chaperones are not to be confused with folding catalyst proteins, which catalyze chemical reactions responsible for slow steps in folding pathways.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] Examples of folding catalysts are protein disulfide isomerases and peptidyl-prolyl isomerases that may be involved in formation of disulfide bonds or interconversion between cis and trans stereoisomers of peptide group.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] Chaperones are shown to be critical in the process of protein folding *in vivo* because they provide the protein with the aid needed to assume its proper alignments and conformations efficiently enough to become "biologically relevant".
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] A fully denatured protein lacks both tertiary and secondary structure, and exists as a so-called random coil.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] Under certain conditions some proteins can refold; however, in many cases, denaturation is irreversible.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] Cells sometimes protect their proteins against the denaturing influence of heat with enzymes known as heat shock proteins (a type of chaperone), which assist other proteins both in folding and in remaining folded.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] Heat shock proteins have been found in all species examined, from bacteria to humans, suggesting that they evolved very early and have an important function.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] Some proteins never fold in cells at all except with the assistance of chaperones which either isolate individual proteins so that their folding is not interrupted by interactions with other proteins or help to unfold misfolded proteins, allowing them to refold into the correct native structure.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] This function is crucial to prevent the risk of precipitation into insoluble amorphous aggregates.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] The external factors involved in protein denaturation or disruption of the native state include temperature, external fields (electric, magnetic), molecular crowding, and even the limitation of space (i.e. confinement), which can have a big influence on the folding of proteins.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] High concentrations of solutes, extremes of pH, mechanical forces, and the presence of chemical denaturants can contribute to protein denaturation, as well.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] These individual factors are categorized together as stresses.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] Chaperones are shown to exist in increasing concentrations during times of cellular stress and help the proper folding of emerging proteins as well as denatured or misfolded ones.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] Under some conditions proteins will not fold into their biochemically functional forms.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] Temperatures above or below the range that cells tend to live in will cause thermally unstable proteins to unfold or denature (this is why boiling makes an egg white turn opaque).
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] Protein thermal stability is far from constant, however; for example, hyperthermophilic archaea have been found that grow at temperatures as high as 122 °C, which of course requires that their full complement of vital proteins and protein assemblies be stable at that temperature or above.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] The bacterium *E. coli* is the host for bacteriophage T4, and the phage encoded gp31 protein (P17313) appears to be structurally and functionally homologous to *E. coli* chaperone protein GroES and able to substitute for it in the assembly of bacteriophage T4 virus particles during infection.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] Like GroES, gp31 forms a stable complex with GroEL chaperonin that is absolutely necessary for the folding and assembly in vivo of the bacteriophage T4 major capsid protein gp23.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] For example, the KaiB protein switches fold throughout the day, acting as a clock for cyanobacteria.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] It has been estimated that around 0.5–4% of PDB (Protein Data Bank) proteins switch folds.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] A protein is considered to be misfolded if it cannot achieve its normal native state.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] This can be due to mutations in the amino acid sequence or to a disruption of the normal folding process by external factors.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] The misfolded protein typically contains beta sheets (β-sheets) that are organized in a supramolecular arrangement known as a cross-β structure.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] These β-sheet-rich assemblies are very stable, very insoluble, and generally resistant to proteolysis.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] The structural stability of these fibrillar assemblies is caused by extensive interactions between the protein monomers, formed by backbone hydrogen bonds between their β-strands.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] The misfolding of proteins can trigger the further misfolding and accumulation of other proteins into aggregates or oligomers.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] The increased levels of aggregated proteins in the cell leads to formation of amyloid-like structures which can cause neurodegenerative disorders and cell death.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] The amyloids are fibrillary structures that contain intermolecular hydrogen bonds which are highly insoluble and made from converted protein aggregates.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] Therefore, the proteasome pathway may not be efficient enough to degrade the misfolded proteins prior to aggregation.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] Misfolded proteins can interact with one another and form structured aggregates and gain toxicity through intermolecular interactions.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] These age onset degenerative diseases are associated with the aggregation of misfolded proteins into insoluble, extracellular aggregates and/or intracellular inclusions including cross-β amyloid fibrils.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] It is not completely clear whether the aggregates are the cause or merely a reflection of the loss of protein homeostasis, the balance between synthesis, folding, aggregation and protein turnover.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] Recently the European Medicines Agency approved the use of Tafamidis or Vyndaqel (a kinetic stabilizer of tetrameric transthyretin) for the treatment of transthyretin amyloid diseases.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] This suggests that the process of amyloid fibril formation (and not the fibrils themselves) causes the degeneration of post-mitotic tissue in human amyloid diseases.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] Misfolding and excessive degradation instead of folding and function leads to a number of proteinopathies, diseases such as antitrypsin-associated emphysema, cystic fibrosis and the lysosomal storage diseases, where loss of function is the origin of the disorder.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] While protein replacement therapy has historically been used to correct the latter disorders, an emerging approach is to use pharmaceutical chaperones to fold mutated proteins to render them functional.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] While inferences about protein folding can be made through mutation studies, typically, experimental techniques for studying protein folding rely on the gradual unfolding or folding of proteins and observing conformational changes using standard non-crystallographic techniques.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] X-ray crystallography is one of the more efficient and important methods for attempting to decipher the three dimensional configuration of a folded protein.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] To be able to conduct X-ray crystallography, the protein under investigation must be located inside a crystal lattice.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] To place a protein inside a crystal lattice, one must have a suitable solvent for crystallization, obtain a pure protein at supersaturated levels in solution, and precipitate the crystals in solution.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] Once a protein is crystallized, X-ray beams can be concentrated through the crystal lattice which would diffract the beams or shoot them outwards in various directions.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] These exiting beams are correlated to the specific three-dimensional configuration of the protein enclosed within.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] The X-rays specifically interact with the electron clouds surrounding the individual atoms within the protein crystal lattice and produce a discernible diffraction pattern.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] Only by relating the electron density clouds with the amplitude of the X-rays can this pattern be read and lead to assumptions of the phases or phase angles involved that complicate this method.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] Without the relation established through a mathematical basis known as Fourier transform, the "phase problem" would render predicting the diffraction patterns very difficult.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] Emerging methods like multiple isomorphous replacement use the presence of a heavy metal ion to diffract the X-rays into a more predictable manner, reducing the number of variables involved and resolving the phase problem.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] Fluorescence spectroscopy is a highly sensitive method for studying the folding state of proteins.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] Three amino acids, phenylalanine (Phe), tyrosine (Tyr) and tryptophan (Trp), have intrinsic fluorescence properties, but only Tyr and Trp are used experimentally because their quantum yields are high enough to give good fluorescence signals.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] Both Trp and Tyr are excited by a wavelength of 280 nm, whereas only Trp is excited by a wavelength of 295 nm.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] Because of their aromatic character, Trp and Tyr residues are often found fully or partially buried in the hydrophobic core of proteins, at the interface between two protein domains, or at the interface between subunits of oligomeric proteins.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] In this apolar environment, they have high quantum yields and therefore high fluorescence intensities.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] Upon disruption of the protein's tertiary or quaternary structure, these side chains become more exposed to the hydrophilic environment of the solvent, and their quantum yields decrease, leading to low fluorescence intensities.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] For Trp residues, the wavelength of their maximal fluorescence emission also depend on their environment.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] Fluorescence spectroscopy can be used to characterize the equilibrium unfolding of proteins by measuring the variation in the intensity of fluorescence emission or in the wavelength of maximal emission as functions of a denaturant value.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] The denaturant can be a chemical molecule (urea, guanidinium hydrochloride), temperature, pH, pressure, etc.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] The equilibrium between the different but discrete protein states, i.e. native state, intermediate states, unfolded state, depends on the denaturant value; therefore, the global fluorescence signal of their equilibrium mixture also depends on this value.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] One thus obtains a profile relating the global protein signal to the denaturant value.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] The profile of equilibrium unfolding may enable one to detect and identify intermediates of unfolding.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] General equations have been developed by Hugues Bedouelle to obtain the thermodynamic parameters that characterize the unfolding equilibria for homomeric or heteromeric proteins, up to trimers and potentially tetramers, from such profiles.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] Fluorescence spectroscopy can be combined with fast-mixing devices such as stopped flow, to measure protein folding kinetics, generate a chevron plot and derive a Phi value analysis.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] Circular dichroism is one of the most general and basic tools to study protein folding.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] Circular dichroism spectroscopy measures the absorption of circularly polarized light.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] In proteins, structures such as alpha helices and beta sheets are chiral, and thus absorb such light.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] The absorption of this light acts as a marker of the degree of foldedness of the protein ensemble.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] This technique has been used to measure equilibrium unfolding of the protein by measuring the change in this absorption as a function of denaturant concentration or temperature.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] A denaturant melt measures the free energy of unfolding as well as the protein's m value, or denaturant dependence.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] A temperature melt measures the denaturation temperature (Tm) of the protein.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] As for fluorescence spectroscopy, circular-dichroism spectroscopy can be combined with fast-mixing devices such as stopped flow to measure protein folding kinetics and to generate chevron plots.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] The more recent developments of vibrational circular dichroism (VCD) techniques for proteins, currently involving Fourier transform (FT) instruments, provide powerful means for determining protein conformations in solution even for very large protein molecules.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] Such VCD studies of proteins can be combined with X-ray diffraction data for protein crystals, FT-IR data for protein solutions in heavy water (D2O), or quantum computations.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] Protein nuclear magnetic resonance (NMR) is able to collect protein structural data by inducing a magnet field through samples of concentrated protein.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] In NMR, depending on the chemical environment, certain nuclei will absorb specific radio-frequencies.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] Because protein structural changes operate on a time scale from ns to ms, NMR is especially equipped to study intermediate structures in timescales of ps to s.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] Some of the main techniques for studying proteins structure and non-folding protein structural changes include COSY, TOCSY, HSQC, time relaxation (T1 & T2), and NOE.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] NOE is especially useful because magnetization transfers can be observed between spatially proximal hydrogens are observed.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] Different NMR experiments have varying degrees of timescale sensitivity that are appropriate for different protein structural changes.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] NOE can pick up bond vibrations or side chain rotations, however, NOE is too sensitive to pick up protein folding because it occurs at larger timescale.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] Because protein folding takes place in about 50 to 3000 s−1 CPMG Relaxation dispersion and chemical exchange saturation transfer have become some of the primary techniques for NMR analysis of folding.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] In addition, both techniques are used to uncover excited intermediate states in the protein folding landscape.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] To do this, CPMG Relaxation dispersion takes advantage of the spin echo phenomenon.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] This technique exposes the target nuclei to a 90 pulse followed by one or more 180 pulses.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] As the nuclei refocus, a broad distribution indicates the target nuclei is involved in an intermediate excited state.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] By looking at Relaxation dispersion plots the data collect information on the thermodynamics and kinetics between the excited and ground.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] Saturation Transfer measures changes in signal from the ground state as excited states become perturbed.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] It uses weak radio frequency irradiation to saturate the excited state of a particular nuclei which transfers its saturation to the ground state.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] This signal is amplified by decreasing the magnetization (and the signal) of the ground state.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] The main limitations in NMR is that its resolution decreases with proteins that are larger than 25 kDa and is not as detailed as X-ray crystallography.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] Additionally, protein NMR analysis is quite difficult and can propose multiple solutions from the same NMR spectrum.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] In a study focused on the folding of an amyotrophic lateral sclerosis involved protein SOD1, excited intermediates were studied with relaxation dispersion and Saturation transfer.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] SOD1 had been previously tied to many disease causing mutants which were assumed to be involved in protein aggregation, however the mechanism was still unknown.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] By using Relaxation Dispersion and Saturation Transfer experiments many excited intermediate states were uncovered misfolding in the SOD1 mutants.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] Dual polarisation interferometry is a surface-based technique for measuring the optical properties of molecular layers.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] Similar to circular dichroism, the stimulus for folding can be a denaturant or temperature.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] The study of protein folding has been greatly advanced in recent years by the development of fast, time-resolved techniques.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] Experimenters rapidly trigger the folding of a sample of unfolded protein and observe the resulting dynamics.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] Fast techniques in use include ultrafast mixing of solutions, photochemical methods, and laser temperature jump spectroscopy.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] Among the many scientists who have contributed to the development of these techniques are Heinrich Roder, Terry Oas, Harry Gray, Martin Gruebele, Brian Dyer, William Eaton, Sheena Radford, Chris Dobson, Alan Fersht, Bengt Nölting and Lars Konermann.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] Proteolysis is routinely used to probe the fraction unfolded under a wide range of solution conditions (e.g. fast parallel proteolysis (FASTpp).
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] Single molecule techniques such as optical tweezers and AFM have been used to understand protein folding mechanisms of isolated proteins as well as proteins with chaperones.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] Optical tweezers have been used to stretch single protein molecules from their C- and N-termini and unfold them to allow study of the subsequent refolding.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] It was discovered – using single molecule optical tweezers measurement – that calcium-bound vWF acts as a shear force sensor in the blood.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] Shear force leads to unfolding of the A2 domain of vWF, whose refolding rate is dramatically enhanced in the presence of calcium.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] It has also been shown that the simple src SH3 domain accesses multiple unfolding pathways under force.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] Biotin painting enables condition-specific cellular snapshots of (un)folded proteins.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] Biotin 'painting' shows a bias towards predicted Intrinsically disordered proteins.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] Computational studies of protein folding includes three main aspects related to the prediction of protein stability, kinetics, and structure.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] A 2013 review summarizes the available computational methods for protein folding.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] In 1969, Cyrus Levinthal noted that, because of the very large number of degrees of freedom in an unfolded polypeptide chain, the molecule has an astronomical number of possible conformations.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] An estimate of 3300 or 10143 was made in one of his papers.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] Based upon the observation that proteins fold much faster than this, Levinthal then proposed that a random conformational search does not occur, and the protein must, therefore, fold through a series of meta-stable intermediate states.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] The configuration space of a protein during folding can be visualized as an energy landscape.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] In addition, the acquisition of the folded state had to become a sufficiently fast process.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] Even though nature has reduced the level of *frustration* in proteins, some degree of it remains up to now as can be observed in the presence of local minima in the energy landscape of proteins.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] A consequence of these evolutionarily selected sequences is that proteins are generally thought to have globally "funneled energy landscapes" (a term coined by José Onuchic) that are largely directed toward the native state.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] This "folding funnel" landscape allows the protein to fold to the native state through any of a large number of pathways and intermediates, rather than being restricted to a single mechanism.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] The theory is supported by both computational simulations of model proteins and experimental studies, and it has been used to improve methods for protein structure prediction and design.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] The description of protein folding by the leveling free-energy landscape is also consistent with the 2nd law of thermodynamics.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] Physically, thinking of landscapes in terms of visualizable potential or total energy surfaces simply with maxima, saddle points, minima, and funnels, rather like geographic landscapes, is perhaps a little misleading.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] The relevant description is really a high-dimensional phase space in which manifolds might take a variety of more complicated topological forms.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] The unfolded polypeptide chain begins at the top of the funnel where it may assume the largest number of unfolded variations and is in its highest energy state.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] Energy landscapes such as these indicate that there are a large number of initial possibilities, but only a single native state is possible; however, it does not reveal the numerous folding pathways that are possible.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] A different molecule of the same exact protein may be able to follow marginally different folding pathways, seeking different lower energy intermediates, as long as the same native structure is reached.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] Different pathways may have different frequencies of utilization depending on the thermodynamic favorability of each pathway.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] This means that if one pathway is found to be more thermodynamically favorable than another, it is likely to be used more frequently in the pursuit of the native structure.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] As the protein begins to fold and assume its various conformations, it always seeks a more thermodynamically favorable structure than before and thus continues through the energy funnel.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] Formation of secondary structures is a strong indication of increased stability within the protein, and only one combination of secondary structures assumed by the polypeptide backbone will have the lowest energy and therefore be present in the native state of the protein.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] Among the first structures to form once the polypeptide begins to fold are alpha helices and beta turns, where alpha helices can form in as little as 100 nanoseconds and beta turns in 1 microsecond.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] There exists a saddle point in the energy funnel landscape where the transition state for a particular protein is found.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] The transition state in the energy funnel diagram is the conformation that must be assumed by every molecule of that protein if the protein wishes to finally assume the native structure.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] No protein may assume the native structure without first passing through the transition state.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] The transition state can be referred to as a variant or premature form of the native state rather than just another intermediary step.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] The folding of the transition state is shown to be rate-determining, and even though it exists in a higher energy state than the native fold, it greatly resembles the native structure.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] Within the transition state, there exists a nucleus around which the protein is able to fold, formed by a process referred to as "nucleation condensation" where the structure begins to collapse onto the nucleus.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] Several large-scale computational projects, such as Rosetta@home, Folding@home and Foldit, target protein folding.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] Long continuous-trajectory simulations have been performed on Anton, a massively parallel supercomputer designed and built around custom ASICs and interconnects by D.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] The longest published result of a simulation performed using Anton as of 2011 was a 2.936 millisecond simulation of NTL9 at 355 K.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] Such simulations are currently able to unfold and refold small proteins (<150 amino acids residues) in equilibrium and predict how mutations affect folding kinetics and stability.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] In 2020 a team of researchers that used AlphaFold, an artificial intelligence (AI) protein structure prediction program developed by DeepMind placed first in CASP, a long-standing structure prediction contest.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] The team achieved a level of accuracy much higher than any other group.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] It scored above 90% for around two-thirds of the proteins in CASP's global distance test (GDT), a test that measures the degree of similarity between the structure predicted by a computational program, and the empirical structure determined experimentally in a lab.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] A score of 100 is considered a complete match, within the distance cutoff used for calculating GDT.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] AlphaFold's protein structure prediction results at CASP were described as "transformational" and "astounding".
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] Some researchers noted that the accuracy is not high enough for a third of its predictions, and that it does not reveal the physical mechanism of protein folding for the protein folding problem to be considered solved.
[src:protein-folding-bio/protein-folding] Nevertheless, it is considered a significant achievement in computational biology and great progress towards a decades-old grand challenge of biology, predicting the structure of proteins.
[src:protein-folding-bio/proteopathy] A **proteinopathy** ([*pref*. protein]; -pathy [*suff*. disease]; **proteinopathies** *pl*.; **proteinopathic** *adj*), or **proteopathy**, **protein conformational disorder**, or **protein misfolding disease**, is a class of diseases in which certain proteins become misfolded.
[src:protein-folding-bio/proteopathy] The structurally abnormal proteins disrupt the function of cells in tissues and organs.
[src:protein-folding-bio/proteopathy] Often the proteins fail to fold into their normal configuration; in this misfolded state, the proteins can become toxic in some way (a toxic gain-of-function) or they can lose their normal function.
[src:protein-folding-bio/proteopathy] The proteinopathies include such diseases as Creutzfeldt–Jakob disease (and a variant associated with mad cow disease) and other prion diseases, Alzheimer's disease, Parkinson's disease, amyloidosis, multiple system atrophy, and a wide range of other disorders.
[src:protein-folding-bio/proteopathy] The term *proteopathy* was first proposed in 2000 by Lary Walker and Harry LeVine.
[src:protein-folding-bio/proteopathy] The concept of proteopathy can trace its origins to the mid-19th century, when, in 1854, Rudolf Virchow coined the term amyloid ("starch-like") to describe a substance in cerebral corpora amylacea that exhibited a chemical reaction resembling that of cellulose.
[src:protein-folding-bio/proteopathy] In 1859, Friedreich and Kekulé demonstrated that, rather than consisting of cellulose, "amyloid" actually is rich in protein.
[src:protein-folding-bio/proteopathy] Subsequent research has shown that many different proteins can form amyloid, and that all amyloids show birefringence in cross-polarized light after staining with the dye Congo red, as well as a fibrillar ultrastructure when viewed with an electron microscope.
[src:protein-folding-bio/proteopathy] However, some proteinaceous lesions lack birefringence and contain few or no classical amyloid fibrils, such as the diffuse deposits of amyloid beta (Aβ) protein in the brains of people with Alzheimer's.
[src:protein-folding-bio/proteopathy] Furthermore, evidence has emerged that small, non-fibrillar protein aggregates known as oligomers are toxic to the cells of an affected organ, and that amyloidogenic proteins in their fibrillar form may be relatively benign.
[src:protein-folding-bio/proteopathy] In most, if not all proteinopathies, a change in the 3-dimensional folding conformation increases the tendency of a specific protein to bind to itself.
[src:protein-folding-bio/proteopathy] In this aggregated form, the protein is resistant to clearance and can interfere with the normal capacity of the affected organs.
[src:protein-folding-bio/proteopathy] In some cases, misfolding of the protein results in a loss of its usual function.
[src:protein-folding-bio/proteopathy] Because proteins share a common structural feature known as the polypeptide backbone, all proteins have the potential to misfold under some circumstances.
[src:protein-folding-bio/proteopathy] However, only a relatively small number of proteins are linked to proteopathic disorders, possibly due to structural idiosyncrasies of the vulnerable proteins.
[src:protein-folding-bio/proteopathy] For example, proteins that are normally unfolded or relatively unstable as monomers (that is, as single, unbound protein molecules) are more likely to misfold into an abnormal conformation.
[src:protein-folding-bio/proteopathy] In nearly all instances, the disease-causing molecular configuration involves an increase in beta-sheet secondary structure of the protein.
[src:protein-folding-bio/proteopathy] The abnormal proteins in some proteopathies have been shown to fold into multiple 3-dimensional shapes; these variant, proteinaceous structures are defined by their different pathogenic, biochemical, and conformational properties.
[src:protein-folding-bio/proteopathy] They have been most thoroughly studied with regard to prion disease, and are referred to as protein strains.
[src:protein-folding-bio/proteopathy] The likelihood that proteinopathy will develop is increased by certain risk factors that promote the self-assembly of a protein.
[src:protein-folding-bio/proteopathy] These include destabilizing changes in the primary amino acid sequence of the protein, post-translational modifications (such as hyperphosphorylation), changes in temperature or pH, an increase in production of a protein, or a decrease in its clearance.
[src:protein-folding-bio/proteopathy] Advancing age is a strong risk factor, as is traumatic brain injury.
[src:protein-folding-bio/proteopathy] In the aging brain, multiple proteopathies can overlap.
[src:protein-folding-bio/proteopathy] For example, in addition to tauopathy and Aβ-amyloidosis (which coexist as key pathologic features of Alzheimer's disease), many Alzheimer patients have concomitant synucleinopathy (Lewy bodies) in the brain.
[src:protein-folding-bio/proteopathy] It is hypothesized that chaperones and co-chaperones (proteins that assist protein folding) may antagonize proteotoxicity during aging and in protein misfolding-diseases to maintain proteostasis.
[src:protein-folding-bio/proteopathy] Some proteins can be induced to form abnormal assemblies by exposure to the same (or similar) protein that has folded into a disease-causing conformation, a process called 'seeding' or 'permissive templating'.
[src:protein-folding-bio/proteopathy] In this way, the disease state can be brought about in a susceptible host by the introduction of diseased tissue extract from an affected donor.
[src:protein-folding-bio/proteopathy] The best known forms of inducible proteopathy are prion diseases, which can be transmitted by exposure of a host organism to purified prion protein in a disease-causing conformation.
[src:protein-folding-bio/proteopathy] In all of these instances, an aberrant form of the protein itself appears to be the pathogenic agent.
[src:protein-folding-bio/proteopathy] In some cases, the deposition of one type of protein can be experimentally induced by aggregated assemblies of other proteins that are rich in β-sheet structure, possibly because of structural complementarity of the protein molecules.
[src:protein-folding-bio/proteopathy] For example, AA amyloidosis can be stimulated in mice by such diverse macromolecules as silk, the yeast amyloid Sup35, and curli fibrils from the bacterium *Escherichia coli*.
[src:protein-folding-bio/proteopathy] AII amyloid can be induced in mice by a variety of β-sheet rich amyloid fibrils, and cerebral tauopathy can be induced by brain extracts that are rich in aggregated Aβ.
[src:protein-folding-bio/proteopathy] There is also experimental evidence for cross-seeding between prion protein and Aβ.
[src:protein-folding-bio/proteopathy] In general, such heterologous seeding is less efficient than is seeding by a corrupted form of the same protein.
[src:protein-folding-bio/proteopathy] The development of effective treatments for many proteopathies has been challenging.
[src:protein-folding-bio/proteopathy] For example, in Alzheimer's disease, researchers are seeking ways to reduce the production of the disease-associated protein Aβ by inhibiting the enzymes that free it from its parent protein.
[src:protein-folding-bio/proteopathy] Another strategy is to use antibodies to neutralize specific proteins by active or passive immunization.
[src:protein-folding-bio/proteopathy] In some proteopathies, inhibiting the toxic effects of protein oligomers might be beneficial.
[src:protein-folding-bio/proteopathy] For example, Amyloid A (AA) amyloidosis can be reduced by treating the inflammatory state that increases the amount of the protein in the blood (referred to as serum amyloid A, or SAA).
[src:protein-folding-bio/proteopathy] In immunoglobulin light chain amyloidosis (AL amyloidosis), chemotherapy can be used to lower the number of the blood cells that make the light chain protein that forms amyloid in various bodily organs.
[src:protein-folding-bio/proteopathy] Transthyretin (TTR) amyloidosis (ATTR) results from the deposition of misfolded TTR in multiple organs.
[src:protein-folding-bio/proteopathy] Because TTR is mainly produced in the liver, TTR amyloidosis can be slowed in some hereditary cases by liver transplantation.
[src:protein-folding-bio/proteopathy] TTR amyloidosis also can be treated by stabilizing the normal assemblies of the protein (called tetramers because they consist of four TTR molecules bound together).
[src:protein-folding-bio/proteopathy] Stabilization prevents individual TTR molecules from escaping, misfolding, and aggregating into amyloid.
[src:protein-folding-bio/proteopathy] Several other treatment strategies for proteopathies are being investigated, including small molecules and biologic medicines such as small interfering RNAs, antisense oligonucleotides, peptides, and engineered immune cells.
[src:protein-folding-bio/proteopathy] In some cases, multiple therapeutic agents may be combined to improve effectiveness.
